A '''cataract''' is a clouding of the [[lens (anatomy)|lens]] inside the [[eye]] which leads to a decrease in vision. It is the most common cause of blindness and is conventionally treated with surgery. Visual loss occurs because [[Opacity (optics)|opacification]] of the lens obstructs light from passing and being focused on to the [[retina]] at the back of the eye.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Quillen DA |title=Common causes of vision loss in elderly patients |journal=Am Fam Physician |volume=60 |issue=1 |pages=99–108 |year=1999 |month=July |pmid=10414631 |url=http://www.aafp.org/afp/990700ap/99.html}}</ref>

It is most commonly due to [[senescence|biological aging]] but there are a wide variety of other causes. Over time, yellow-brown pigment is deposited within the lens and this, together with disruption of the normal architecture of the lens fibers, leads to reduced transmission of light, which in turn leads to visual problems. 

Those with cataract commonly experience difficulty appreciating colors and changes in contrast, driving, reading, recognizing faces, and experience problems coping with glare from bright lights.<ref name="Allen-2006">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Allen | first1 = D. | last2 = Vasavada | first2 = A. | title = Cataract and surgery for cataract. | journal = BMJ | volume = 333 | issue = 7559 | pages = 128–32 | month = Jul | year = 2006 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.333.7559.128 | PMID = 16840470 }}</ref>

== Signs and symptoms ==
[[File:Cataracts due to Congenital Rubella Syndrome (CRS) PHIL 4284 lores.jpg|thumb|Bilateral cataracts in an infant due to [[congenital rubella syndrome]] ]]
Signs and symptoms  vary depending on the type of cataract, though there is considerable overlap. People with nuclear sclerotic or brunescent cataract, often notice a [[Vision loss|reduction of vision]]. Those with posterior supcapsular cataract usually complain of [[Glare (vision)|glare]] as their major symptom.<ref>{{cite web|title=Posterior Supcapsular Cataract |work=Digital Reference of Ophthalmology |url=http://dro.hs.columbia.edu/lc1.htm|publisher=Edward S. Harkness Eye Institute, Department of Ophthalmology of Columbia University|year=2003|accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

The severity of cataract formation, assuming that no other eye disease is present, is judged primarily by [[visual acuity]] test. The appropriateness of surgery depends on a patient's particular functional and visual needs and other risk factors, all of which may vary widely.<ref name=vaughan>{{cite book|last=Emmett T. Cunningham, Paul Riordan-Eva|title=Vaughan & Asbury's general ophthalmology.|publisher=McGraw-Hill Medical|isbn=978-0071634205|edition=18th ed.}}</ref>

== Causes ==

===Age===
Age is the most common cause.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Courtney P |title=The National Cataract Surgery Survey: I. Method and descriptive features |journal=Eye (Lond) |volume=6 |issue=Pt 5 |pages=487–92 |year=1992 |pmid=1286712 |doi=10.1038/eye.1992.103 |url=}}</ref> Lens proteins [[Denaturation (biochemistry)|denature]] and degrade over time and this process is accelerated by diseases such as diabetes and hypertension. With the passage of time, environmental factors including toxins, radiation and UV light have an accumulative effect. These effects are worsened by the loss of protective and restorative mechanisms due to alterations in gene expression and chemical processes within the eye.<ref name="yanoff">{{cite book |author=Duker, Jay S.; Myron Yanoff MD; Yanoff, Myron; Jay S. Duker MD |title=Ophthalmology |publisher=Mosby/Elsevier |location=St. Louis, Mo |year=2009 |isbn=0-323-04332-1 }}</ref>

===Trauma===
Blunt trauma causes swelling, thickening and whitening of the lens fibers. While the swelling normally resolves with time, the white color may remain. In severe blunt trauma, or injuries which penetrate the eye, the capsule in which the lens sits can be damaged. This allows water from other parts of the eye to rapidly enter the lens leading to swelling and then whitening, obstructing light from reaching the retina at the back of the eye.

===Radiation===
Ultraviolet light, specifically UV-B, has been shown to cause cataract and there is some evidence that sunglasses worn at an early age can slow its development  in later life.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Sliney DH |title=UV radiation ocular exposure dosimetry |journal=Doc Ophthalmol |volume=88 |issue=3-4 |pages=243–54 |year=1994 |pmid=7634993 }}</ref> Most UV light from the sun is filtered out by the atmosphere but airline pilots often have high rates of cataract because of the increased levels of UV radiation in the upper atmosphere.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Rafnsson | first = V | coauthors = Olafsdottir E, Hrafnkelsson J, Sasaki H, Arnarsson A, Jonasson F | title = Cosmic radiation increases the risk of nuclear cataract in airline pilots: a population-based case-control study | journal = Arch Ophthalmol | volume = 123 | pages = 1102–5 | doi = 10.1001/archopht.123.8.1102 | year = 2005 | pmid = 16087845 | issue = 8}}</ref>  It is hypothesised that [[Ozone depletion|depletion of the ozone layer]] and a consequent increase in levels of UV light on the ground may increase future rates of cataracts.<ref name="Dobson2005">{{cite doi|10.1136/bmj.331.7528.1292-d}}</ref>  It has also been recognized, from experimental animal studies and epidemiological studies in humans, that microwaves can cause cataract. The mechanism is unclear but may include changes in heat sensitive enzymes that normally protect cell proteins in the lens. Another mechanism that has been advanced is direct damage to the lens from pressure waves induced in the aqueous humor. 
Cataracts have also been associated with ionizing radiation such as X-rays. In addition to the mechanisms already mentioned, the addition of damage to the DNA of the lens cells has been considered.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lipman RM, Tripathi BJ, Tripathi RC |title=Cataracts induced by microwave and ionizing radiation |journal=Surv Ophthalmol |volume=33 |issue=3 |pages=200–10 |year=1988 |pmid=3068822 |doi= |url=}}</ref>  Finally, electric and heat injuries denature and whiten the lens itself as a result of direct protein coagulation.<ref name="yanoff" /> This is the same process through which the clear albumin of an egg becomes white and opaque after cooking. These types of cataract are often seen in glass blowers and furnace workers.

===Genetics===
There is a strong genetic component in the development of cataract, most commonly through mechanisms that protect and maintain the lens. The presence of cataract in childhood or early life can occasionally be due to a particular syndrome.

Examples of  [[Chromosomal disorder|Chromosome abnormalities]] associated with cataract include: [[1q21.1 deletion syndrome]], [[Cri-du-chat syndrome]], [[Down syndrome]], [[Patau's syndrome]], [[Trisomy 18]] ([[Edward's syndrome]]) and [[Turner's syndrome]].

Examples of [[Single-gene disorder]] include: [[Alport's syndrome]], [[Conradi's syndrome]], [[Myotonic dystrophy]], [[Oculocerebrorenal syndrome]] or [[Lowe syndrome]]

===Skin diseases===

The skin and the lens have the same embryological origin and can be affected by similar diseases. Those with [[Atopic dermatitis]] and [[Eczema]] will occasionally develop shield ulcers cataract. [[Ichthyosis]] is an autosomal recessive disorder associated with cuneiform cataract and nuclear sclerosis. Basal-cell nevus and [[Pemphigus]] have similar associations.

===Drug use===

Smoking has been shown to lead to a two-fold increase in the rate of nuclear sclerotic cataract and a three-fold increase in posterior subcapsular cataract.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Christen WG, Manson JE, Seddon JM, ''et al.'' |title=A prospective study of cigarette smoking and risk of cataract in men |journal=JAMA |volume=268 |issue=8 |pages=989–93 |year=1992 |month=August |pmid=1501324 }}</ref> There is conflicting evidence over the effect of alcohol. Some surveys have shown a link but others that have followed patients over time have not.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Wang S, Wang JJ, Wong TY |title=Alcohol and eye diseases |journal=Surv Ophthalmol |volume=53 |issue=5 |pages=512–25 |year=2008 |pmid=18929762 |doi=10.1016/j.survophthal.2008.06.003 }}</ref>

===Medications===
Some drugs, such as [[corticosteroid]]s, and the antipsychotic drug [[quetiapine]] can induce cataract development,<ref name=spencer>{{cite journal |author=Spencer R., Andelman S. |title=Steroid cataracts. Posterior subcapsular cataract formation in rheumatoid arthritis patients on long term steroid therapy |journal=Arch Ophthalmol |volume=74 |pages=38–41 |year= 1965|pmid=14303339}}</ref> as may [[haloperidol]],<ref>{{cite journal |journal=CNS Drugs |date=2010 Jun |volume=24 |issue=6 |pages=501–26 |doi= 10.2165/11533180-000000000-00000 |title=Ocular adverse effects of common psychotropic agents: a review |author=Richa S, Yazbek JC |pmid=20443647 }}</ref> [[miotics]],<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Revue médicale de Liège |date=1998 Dec |volume=53 |issue=12 |pages=766–9 |trans_title=Drug-induced cataracts |title=Cataractes incitées de médicament |language=French |author=van den Brûle J, Degueldre F, Galand A |pmid=9927876}}</ref> and triparanol.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nlm.nih.gov/cgi/mesh/2012/MB_cgi?mode=&term=Triparanol&field=entry |title=Triperanol |publisher=National Library of Medicine |work=MeSH |accessdate=2013-02-06}}</ref>  Cataracts can also be caused by [[iodine deficiency]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1159/000267127 |author=Buchberger W, Winkler R, Moser M, Rieger G |year=1991 |title=Influence of iodide on cataractogenesis in Emory mice | journal=Ophthalmic Res |volume=23 |issue=6|pages=303–8 |pmid=1803312 }}</ref>

