Age-related cataracts are responsible for 51% of world blindness, about 20 million people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Priority eye diseases: Cataract |work=Prevention of Blindness and Visual Impairment |publisher=World Health Organization |url=http://www.who.int/blindness/causes/priority/en/index1.html}} WHO.int], | .</ref> Globally, cataracts cause moderate to severe disability in 53.8&nbsp;million (2004), 52.2&nbsp;million of whom are in low and middle income countries.<ref>{{cite book|last=Organization|first=World Health|title=The global burden of disease : 2004 update.|year=2008|publisher=World Health Organization|location=Geneva, Switzerland|isbn=9789241563710|pages=35}}</ref>

In many countries surgical services are inadequate, and cataracts remain the leading cause of blindness.  Even where surgical services are available, low vision associated with cataracts may still be prevalent as a result of long waits for, and barriers to, surgery - such as cost, lack of information and transportation problems.

In the United States, age-related lens changes have been reported in 42% between the ages of 52 and 64,<ref name="Sperduto">{{cite journal | author = Sperduto RD, Seigel D., Seigel D. Sperduto RD | year = 1980 | month = Jul | title = Senile lens and senile macular changes in a population-based sample | journal = Am J Ophthalmol | volume = 90 | issue = 1| pages = 86–91 | pmid = 7395962 }}</ref> 60% between the ages 65 and 74,<ref>{{cite journal | author = Kahn HA, Leibowitz HM, Ganley JP, Kini MM, Colton T, Nickerson RS, Dawber TR | year = 1977 | month = Jul | title = The Framingham Eye Study. I. Outline and major prevalence findings |journal = Am J Epidemiol | volume = 106 | issue = 1| pages = 17–32 | pmid = 879158 }}</ref> and 91% between the ages of 75 and 85.<ref name="Sperduto"/> Cataracts affect 22.3 million Americans with a direct medical cost of $6.8 billion annually.<ref>{{cite web |title= Prevent Eye Damage and Protect Yourself from UV Radiation |url=http://health.ltgovernors.com/prevent-eye-damage-and-protect-yourself-from-uv-radiation.html}}</ref>

In the Eastern Mediterranean Region, Cataract is responsible for over 51% of  blindness. Access to eye care in many countries on this region is limited.<ref>{{cite web |title=Health Topics: Cataract  |publisher=World Health Organization - Eastern Mediterranean Regional Office |url=http://www.emro.who.int/health-topics/cataract/}}</ref>

== History ==
The first references to cataract and its treatment in [[Ancient Rome]] are found in 29 AD in ''De Medicinae'', the work of the Latin encyclopedist [[Aulus Cornelius Celsus]].<ref>{{cite book |ol=5225311W |title=De Medicinae |author=[[Aulus Cornelius Celsus]], G. F. Collier (transl.) |year=1831}}</ref> The Romans were pioneers in the health arena - particularly in the area of eye care.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/7194352.stm |title=The Romans carried out cataract ops |date=February 9, 2008 |work= BBC News |first=Jane |last=Elliott}}</ref>

Other early accounts are found in [[Sanskrit]]. Cataract surgery was described by the [[Ayurveda|Indian physician]], [[Suśruta]] (fl. ca. 200 AD).<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Suśruta]], P. V. Sharma (trans.) |title=Suśruta-Saṃhitā |location=Varanasi |publisher=Caukhambha Visvabharati |year=2000 |volume=1 |page=iv |ol=160267M }}</ref>  A translation from the original Sanskrit can be found at [[Cataract surgery#History|Cataract Surgery]].

The [[Ophthalmology in medieval Islam|Muslim ophthalmologist]] Ammar ibn Ali, in his ''Choice of Eye Diseases'', written circa 1000 CE, wrote of his invention of a [[syringe]] and the technique of cataract extraction while [[experiment]]ing with it on a patient.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Origins of Neuroscience: A History of Explorations Into Brain Function|first=Stanley|last=Finger|year=1994|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=0-19-514694-8|page=70|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>

===Etymology===
''Cataract'' is derived from the [[Latin]] ''cataracta'' meaning "waterfall" and from the [[Greek language|Greek]] καταράκτης (''kataraktēs'') or καταρράκτης (''katarrhaktēs''), "down-rushing",<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dkatarra%2Fkths καταρράκτης], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref> from καταράσσω (''katarassō'') meaning "to dash down"<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dkatara%2Fssw καταράσσω], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott,''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref> (from ''kata''-, "down"; ''arassein'', "to strike, dash").<ref>{{cite web |title=cataract |date=29 October 2003 |work=Word of the Day |publisher=Dictionary.com |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/wordoftheday/archive/2003/10/29.html}}<br/>{{cite web |title=cataract |work=Oxford Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |url=http://oxforddictionaries.com/view/entry/m_en_gb0128960#m_en_gb0128960cataract}}</ref> As rapidly running water turns white, so the term may have been used metaphorically to describe the similar appearance of mature ocular opacities. In Latin, ''cataracta'' had the alternate meaning "[[portcullis]]"<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0059%3Aentry%3Dcataracta cataracta], Charlton T. Lewis, Charles Short, ''A Latin Dictionary'', on Perseus</ref> and  the name possibly passed through French to form the English meaning "eye disease" (early 15th century), on the notion of "obstruction".<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=cataract Online Etymology Dictionary<!-- Bot generated title -->], etymonline.com</ref> Early Persian physicians called the term ''nazul-i-ah'', or "descent of the water" - vulgarised into waterfall disease or cataract - believing such blindness to be caused by an outpouring of corrupt [[humorism|humour]] into the eye.<ref>[http://wordcraft.infopop.cc/eve/forums/a/tpc/f/756604565/m/2881057435 Mistaken Science — Topic Powered by eve community], Wordcraft Forums, wordcraft.infopop.cc</ref>

==Research==
[[acetylcarnosine|N-acetylcarnosine]] have been investigated as a medical treatment for cataract. The drops are believed to work by reducing [[oxidation]] and [[glycation]] damage in the lens, particularly reducing [[crystallin]] crosslinking.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1111/j.1463-5224.2006.00492.x | author = Williams DL, Munday P | year = 2006 | title = The effect of a topical antioxidant formulation including N-acetyl carnosine on canine cataract: a preliminary study | journal = Vet Ophthalmol | volume = 9 | issue = 5| pages = 311–6 | pmid = 16939459 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Guo Y, Yan H | year = 2006 | title = Preventive effect of carnosine on cataract development | journal = Yan Ke Xue Bao | volume = 22 | issue = 2| pages = 85–8 | pmid = 17162883 }}</ref> Some benefit has been shown in small manufacturer sponsored randomized controlled trials but further independent corroboration is still required.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Toh T, Morton J, Coxon J, Elder MJ |title=Medical treatment of cataract |journal=Clin. Experiment. Ophthalmol. |volume=35 |issue=7 |pages=664–71 |year=2007 |pmid=17894689 |doi=10.1111/j.1442-9071.2007.01559.x |url=}}</ref>

[[Mode-locking|Femtosecond laser]] has been used during cataract surgery. This technique known as femtosecond laser technology and originally used to cut accurate and predictable flaps in LASIK surgery, has been introduced to cataract surgery.  The incision at the junction of the sclera and cornea and the hole in capsule during capsulorhexis, traditionally made with a handheld blade, needle and forceps are dependent on skill and experience of the surgeon. Sophisticated 3-D image of the eyes can be used to guide lasers to make these incisions,  [[Nd:YAG laser]] can also then break up the cataract as in phacoemulsification.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Friedman NJ, Palanker DV, Schuele G, ''et al.'' |title=Femtosecond laser capsulotomy |journal=J Cataract Refract Surg |volume=37 |issue=7 |pages=1189–98 |year=2011 |month=July |pmid=21700099 |doi=10.1016/j.jcrs.2011.04.022 |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0886-3350(11)00728-0}} [http://www.stanford.edu/~palanker/publications/fs%20capsulotomy%20JCRS%202011.pdf as PDF] The authors declare a financial interest in a company producing femtosecond laser equipment.</ref>

